    "The 20 percent standardisable fraction is subject to two key caveats: the stellar initial mass function is assumed to be Salpeter-like and the ellipticity of the lensing mass follows that of the light.",
    "The assumption of a particular IMF sets the stellar-to-dark matter fraction.",
    "Figure 5 shows the importance of this assumption: at very high stellar fraction there are no strongly lensed images with minimal microlensing scatter (Weisenbach et al. 2021).",
    "With a population of lensed SNe, Foxley-Marrable et al. (2018) found that observing the amount of microlensing induced scatter can be used to constrain the IMF of the lens galaxy, with strong sensitivity for lenses with Einstein radius between 0.2 and 0.5.",
    "The assumption that mass follows light produces more elliptical lens mass distributions than is seen in cold-darkmatter-only simulations."
